easurement/">Party Dress <span>(17)</span></a></li></ul></li><li class="active">					<a href="javascript:void(0)" class="nav-sub first"><i class="fa fa-my-menu"></i></a> <a class="second" href="https://corsetacademy.net/categories/#544">Transparent corsets  <span>(4)</span></a><ul class="list-unstyled"><li><a href="javascript:void(0)" class="nav-sub first blank" data-catid="25"><i class="fa fa-my-menu"></i></a> <a class="second" href="https://corsetacademy.net/tutorial-1-getting-acquainted-with-the-model-cutting-a-mock-up/">Corset with Drapery <span>(20)</span></a></li><li><a href="javascript:void(0)" class="nav-sub first blank" data-catid="26"><i class="fa fa-my-menu"></i></a> <a class="second" href="https://corsetacademy.net/tutorial-1-getting-acquainted-with-the-model-and-the-throw-over-sewing-technique/">Corset with Integral Straps <span>(27)</span></a></li><li><a href="javascript:void(0)" class="nav-sub first blank" data-catid="34"><i class="fa fa-my-menu"></i></a> <a class="second" href="https://corsetacademy.net/tutorial-1-getting-acquainted-with-the-model/">Corset with 3-Part Cups <span>(22)</span></a></li><li><a href="javascript:void(0)" class="nav-sub first blank" data-catid="76"><i class="fa fa-my-menu"></i></a> <a class="second" href="https://corsetacademy.net/tutorial-1-getting-acquainted-with-the-model-5/">Corset with a Fancy Cut-Out <span>(22)</span></a></li></ul></li><li class="active">					<a href="javascript:void(0)" class="nav-sub first"><i class="fa fa-my-menu"></i></a> <a class="second" href="https://corsetacademy.net/categories/#3082">Decoration Techniques  <span>(9)</span></a><ul class="list-unstyled"><li><a href="javascript:void(0)" class="nav-sub first blank" data-catid="83"><i class="fa fa-my-menu"></i></a> <a class="second" href="https://corsetacademy.net/tutorial-1-decoration-materials/">Rhinestones Decoration <span>(5)</span></a></li><li><a href="javascript:void(0)" class="nav-sub first blank" data-catid="84"><i class="fa fa-my-menu"></i></a> <a class="second" href="https://corsetacademy.net/tutorial-1-glue-on-half-pearls/">Additional Decoration <span>(5)</span></a></li><li><a href="javascript:void(0)" class="nav-sub first blank" data-catid="85"><i class="fa fa-my-menu"></i></a> <a class="second" href="https://corsetacademy.net/tutorial-1-thick-decoration-element/">Thick Decoration Elements <span>(5)</span></a></li><li><a href="javascript:void(0)" class="nav-sub first blank" data-catid="86"><i class="fa fa-my-menu"></i></a> <a class="second" href="https://corsetacademy.net/tutorial-1-decoration-materials-2/">Wedding Dress Decoration <span>(5)</span></a></li><li><a href="javascript:void(0)" class="nav-sub first blank" data-catid="87"><i class="fa fa-my-menu"></i></a> <a class="second" href="https://corsetacademy.net/tutorial-1-types-of-sequins/">Sequins Decoration <span>(11)</span></a></li><li><a href="javascript:void(0)" class="nav-sub first blank" data-catid="105"><i class="fa fa-my-menu"></i></a> <a class="second" href="https://corsetacademy.net/tutorial-1-marking-the-borders-of-the-decoration/">Casual Garment Decoration <span>(5)</span></a></li><li><a href="javascript:void(0)" class="nav-sub first blank" data-catid="106"><i class="fa fa-my-menu"></i></a> <a class="second" href="https://corsetacademy.net/epaulettes-function-and-materials/">Epaulettes <span>(8)</span></a></li><li><a href="javascript:void(0)" class="nav-sub first blank" data-catid="127"><i class="fa fa-my-menu"></i></a> <a class="second" href="https://corsetacademy.net/tambour-or-luneville-embroidery-part-1/">Tambour or Luneville Embroidery <span>(5)</span></a></li><li><a href="javascript:void(0)" class="nav-sub first blank" data-catid="128"><i class="fa fa-my-menu"></i></a> <a class="second" href="https://corsetacademy.net/the-button-loop-closure-part-1/">The Button Loop Closure <span>(2)</span></a></li></ul></li><li class="active">					<a href="javascript:void(0)" class="nav-sub first"><i class="fa fa-my-menu"></i></a> <a class="second" href="https://corsetacademy.net/categories/#4289">Fancy Dresses for Girls  <span>(5)</span></a><ul class="list-unstyled"><li><a href="javascript:void(0)" class="nav-sub first blank" data-catid="118"><i class="fa fa-my-menu"></i></a> <a class="second" href="https://corsetacademy.net/childrens-body-proportions/">The Law of Proportions in Children's Wear <span>(3)</span></a></li><li><a href="javascript:void(0)" class="nav-sub first blank" data-catid="117"><i class="fa fa-my-menu"></i></a> <a class="second" href="https://corsetacademy.net/tutorial-1-choosing-a-suitable-style-for-the-childs-body-proportions/">Fancy Dress for 3 Years Old Girl <span>(9)</span></a></li><li><a href="javascript:void(0)" class="nav-sub first blank" data-catid="119"><i class="fa fa-my-menu"></i></a> <a class="second" href="https://corsetacademy.net/tutorial-1-choosing-a-suitable-dress/">Fancy Dress for 6 Years Old Girl <span>(16)</span></a></li><li><a href="javascript:void(0)" class="nav-sub first blank" data-catid="120"><i class="fa fa-my-menu"></i></a> <a class="second" href="https://corsetacademy.net/tutorial-1-choosing-a-suitable-style-with-respect-to-the-childs-body-proportions/">Fancy Dress for 9 Years Old Girl <span>(14)</span></a></li><li><a href="javascript:void(0)" class="nav-sub first blank" data-catid="135"><i class="fa fa-my-menu"></i></a> <a class="second" href="https://corsetacademy.net/tutorial-1-choosing-a-suitable-dress-with-regard-to-the-childs-body-proportions/">Fancy Dress for 12 Years Old Girl <span>(14)</span></a></li></ul></li>		</ul></div></div>													<div class="lesson-tab" role="tabpanel">				  <!-- Nav tabs -->				  <ul class="nav nav-tabs" role="tablist">					<li role="presentation" class="active"><a href="#about" aria-controls="about" role="tab" data-toggle="tab">Course details</a></li>																		<li role="presentation"><a href="#transcript" aria-controls="transcript" role="tab" data-toggle="tab">Transcript</a></li>														<li role="presentation"><a href="#pattern" aria-controls="pattern" role="tab" data-toggle="tab">Pattern</a></li>					<li role="presentation"><a href="#diploma" aria-controls="transcript" role="tab" data-toggle="tab">Diploma</a></li>						<li role="presentation"><a class="faq-tab blank" href="#faq" aria-controls="faq" role="tab" data-toggle="tab">FAQs</a></li>				  </ul>				  <!-- Tab panes -->				  <div class="tab-content">				  																									<div role="tabpanel" class="tab-pane active" id="about">											<div class="dark-get-started margin-0">																																											<p><strong><em>Dressmaker’s Treasury&nbsp;</em></strong><strong>is a collection of key tools and skills which every dressmaker needs for successful work.</strong></p><p><strong>I am offering you a great instrument to help you acquire more confidence for fulfilling your creative projects!&nbsp;</strong>You will no longer have any fear of complex sophisticated garments! You will learn to work with mock-ups, make crinolines of non-standard shapes, and sew various kinds of fabric cases for petticoats to enhance the fullness of the main skirt.</p><p><strong>Our main goal at the Corset Academy&nbsp;</strong>is to teach you how to sew wedding and evening garments. And I want you to be able to sew a high-quality garment within a relatively short time.</p><p><strong>I don’t want you to spend lots of time on doing complicated calculations and making basic skirt patterns!</strong></p><p><strong>All necessary materials are included in the course:</strong></p><ul><li><h4>Patterns of four silhouette skirts in the actual size (PDF);</h4></li><li><h4>Patterns of four silhouette skirts in half the actual size for sewing mock-ups and designing new skirt models (PDF);</h4></li><li><h4>Three tables for AUTOMATIC calculation of all parameters required for cutting a trapeze-shaped skirt, a half-circle skirt, and a full-sweep skirt (HTML). These tables contain 18 tabs for calculating necessary parameters for the mentioned types of skirts, horizontal and vertical ruffles, falbalas, and the elastic waistband skirt.</h4></li><li><h4>Three tables for AUTOMATIC calculations with fixed parameters for the trapeze-shaped skirt, the half-circle skirt, and the full-sweep skirt (HTML);</h4></li></ul><h4>Fixed parameters (i.e. measurements) allow you to quickly calculate necessary data for cutting ruffles and falbalas for a skirt of a certain size: consumption of main fabric, lining fabric, decorative materials, etc.</h4><p><strong>Our new course&nbsp;<em>Dressmaker’s Treasury. Wedding Skirts and Petticoats&nbsp;</em>is a collection of important methods and skills which every dressmaker must know in order to achieve good results. It will be equally helpful for beginners and for experienced professionals!</strong></p><p><strong>Every professional dressmaker knows that sewing complex wedding skirts&nbsp;</strong>is not just about sewing together kilometers of fabric. The key thing is correct calculations and your ability to “foresee” the final results and related fabric consumption well before you start cutting and sewing.</p><p>I would also like to emphasize that the skirt from this course is merely a foundation for your own masterpieces. Let your creativity bloom!</p><p><strong>The course&nbsp;is&nbsp;useful both to beginner dressmakers, as well as experienced professionals.</strong></p><p><strong>Enjoy it!</strong></p><p><strong>Author:</strong>&nbsp;Tatiana Kozorovitsky</p><p><strong>Total length:</strong>&nbsp;6h 12m</p>												</div>						</div>										<div role="tabpanel" class="tab-pane" id="transcript">						<div class="overlay"></div>						<!-- BEGIN Schema.org microdata added by the Add-Meta-Tags WordPress plugin --><!-- Scope BEGIN: Article --><div itemscope="" itemtype="http://schema.org/Article"><!-- Scope BEGIN: Organization --><span itemprop="publisher" itemscope="" itemtype="http://schema.org/Organization"><meta itemprop="name" content="Corset Academy"><!-- Scope BEGIN: ImageObject --><span itemprop="logo" itemscope="" itemtype="http://schema.org/ImageObject"><meta itemprop="name" content="Corset Academy logo"><meta itemprop="text" content="Corset Academy logo"><meta itemprop="url" content="https://corsetacademy.net/wp-content/themes/corset/img/logo.png"><meta itemprop="contentUrl" content="https://corsetacademy.net/wp-content/themes/corset/img/logo.png"><meta itemprop="width" content="303"><meta itemprop="height" content="49"><meta itemprop="encodingFormat" content="image/png"></span> <!-- Scope END: ImageObject --><meta itemprop="url" content="https://corsetacademy.net/"><meta itemprop="sameAs" content="https://www.facebook.com/corsetacademy"></span> <!-- Scope END: Organization --><!-- Scope BEGIN: Person --><span itemprop="author" itemscope="" itemtype="http://schema.org/Person"><meta itemprop="name" content="Tatiana Kozorovitsky"><!-- Scope BEGIN: ImageObject --><span itemprop="image" itemscope="" itemtype="http://schema.org/ImageObject"><meta itemprop="url" content="https://corsetacademy.net/wp-content/uploads/MVI_3285.MOV.00_00_31_09.Still001-128x128.jpg"><meta itemprop="contentUrl" content="https://corsetacademy.net/wp-content/uploads/MVI_3285.MOV.00_00_31_09.Still001-128x128.jpg"><meta itemprop="width" content="128"><meta itemprop="height" content="128"><meta itemprop="encodingFormat" content="image/jpeg"></span> <!-- Scope END: ImageObject --><meta itemprop="url" content="https://corsetacademy.net/author/infocorsetacademy-net/"><meta itemprop="sameAs" content="http://www.corsetacademy.net"></span> <!-- Scope END: Person --><meta itemprop="url" content="https://corsetacademy.net/tutorial-25-making-paper-gore-patterns-and-full-size-skirt-pattern/"><meta itemprop="mainEntityOfPage" content="https://corsetacademy.net/tutorial-25-making-paper-gore-patterns-and-full-size-skirt-pattern/"><meta itemprop="datePublished" content="2018-05-07T20:05:43+00:00"><meta itemprop="dateModified" content="2018-05-07T20:05:43+00:00"><meta itemprop="copyrightYear" content="2018"><meta itemprop="inLanguage" content="en_US"><meta itemprop="name" content="Tutorial 25. Making Paper Gore Patterns and Full-Size Skirt Pattern."><meta itemprop="headline" content="Tutorial 25. Making Paper Gore Patterns and Full-Size Skirt Pattern."><meta itemprop="description" content="I measured all sides of triangles which need to be inserted in the skirt to make it flared, drew them schematically on a piece of paper, and wrote down all lengths"><meta itemprop="articleSection" content="Wedding Skirts and Petticoats. Practical Part."><meta itemprop="keywords" content="wedding skirts and petticoats. practical part., video"><!-- Scope BEGIN: ImageObject --><span itemprop="image" itemscope="" itemtype="http://schema.org/ImageObject"><meta itemprop="url" content="https://corsetacademy.net/wp-content/themes/corset/img/logo.png"><meta itemprop="contentUrl" content="https://corsetacademy.net/wp-content/themes/corset/img/logo.png"><meta itemprop="width" content="303"><meta itemprop="height" content="49"><meta itemprop="encodingFormat" content="image/png"></span> <!-- Scope END: ImageObject --><div itemprop="articleBody"><h1>Tutorial 25. Making Paper Gore Patterns and Full-Size Skirt Pattern.</h1><p><strong>During the previous tutorials, I measured all sides of triangles which need to be inserted in the skirt to make it flared, drew them schematically on a piece of paper, and wrote down all lengths. </strong></p><p><img class="img-responsive center-block" src="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/Dressmaker_Essential_Skirts/Transcripts/Tutorial%2025.files/image002.jpg" alt=""></p><p><strong>Now, in order to make a paper gore pattern, I need to draw the flare triangle on paper and add corresponding parts of the main skirt along its sides, i.e. the intermediate parts between the main skirt and the sides of the triangle. </strong>In order to do this, I have cut out these parts following the marked cutting lines. You should remember to add seam allowances, too.</p><p><strong>I am making a gore pattern corresponding with the triangle with sides 1 and 2 (in half scale). </strong></p><p><strong>I draw triangle 1-2 in the empty corner of the paper pattern. </strong></p><p><strong><br><img class="img-responsive center-block" src="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/Dressmaker_Essential_Skirts/Transcripts/Tutorial%2025.files/image004.jpg" alt=""></strong></p><p><strong><br><img class="img-responsive center-block" src="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/Dressmaker_Essential_Skirts/Transcripts/Tutorial%2025.files/image006.jpg" alt=""></strong></p><p><strong><br><img class="img-responsive center-block" src="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/Dressmaker_Essential_Skirts/Transcripts/Tutorial%2025.files/image008.jpg" alt=""></strong></p><p><strong><br><img class="img-responsive center-block" src="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/Dressmaker_Essential_Skirts/Transcripts/Tutorial%2025.files/image010.jpg" alt=""></strong></p><p><strong>I align side 2 with the corresponding piece separated from the mock-up, pin it down, outline it (red line), add a seam allowance (red dashed line), and cut along. I mark the bottom point of the gore of the skirt. </strong></p><p><img class="img-responsive center-block" src="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/Dressmaker_Essential_Skirts/Transcripts/Tutorial%2025.files/image012.jpg" alt=""></p><p><img class="img-responsive center-block" src="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/Dressmaker_Essential_Skirts/Transcripts/Tutorial%2025.files/image014.jpg" alt=""></p><p><img class="img-responsive center-block" src="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/Dressmaker_Essential_Skirts/Transcripts/Tutorial%2025.files/image016.jpg" alt=""></p><p><strong>Here is the pattern of gore 1-2 for our mock-up skirt! </strong></p><p><img class="img-responsive center-block" src="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/Dressmaker_Essential_Skirts/Transcripts/Tutorial%2025.files/image018.jpg" alt=""></p><p><strong>The pattern of the triangle with the sides numbered 3 and 4 is made exactly the same way. </strong></p><p><strong>I draw triangle 3-4 in accordance with its dimensions, align the corresponding gore parts cut from the mock-up with sides 3 and 4, pin them down, outline it (red line), add seam allowances (red dashed line), and cut it out. </strong></p><p><strong><br><img class="img-responsive center-block" src="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/Dressmaker_Essential_Skirts/Transcripts/Tutorial%2025.files/image020.jpg" alt=""></strong></p><p><strong><br><img class="img-responsive center-block" src="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/Dressmaker_Essential_Skirts/Transcripts/Tutorial%2025.files/image022.jpg" alt=""></strong></p><p><strong><br><img class="img-responsive center-block" src="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/Dressmaker_Essential_Skirts/Transcripts/Tutorial%2025.files/image024.jpg" alt=""></strong></p><p><strong>I make a pattern of the next gore which corresponds with the flare triangle with sides 5 and 6. </strong></p><p><img class="img-responsive center-block" src="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/Dressmaker_Essential_Skirts/Transcripts/Tutorial%2025.files/image026.jpg" alt=""></p><p><img class="img-responsive center-block" src="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/Dressmaker_Essential_Skirts/Transcripts/Tutorial%2025.files/image028.jpg" alt=""></p><p><img class="img-responsive center-block" src="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/Dressmaker_Essential_Skirts/Transcripts/Tutorial%2025.files/image030.jpg" alt=""></p><p><strong>I make a pattern of the gore which corresponds with the flare triangle with sides 7 and 8. </strong></p><p><strong><br><img class="img-responsive center-block" src="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/Dressmaker_Essential_Skirts/Transcripts/Tutorial%2025.files/image032.jpg" alt=""></strong></p><p><strong><br><img class="img-responsive center-block" src="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/Dressmaker_Essential_Skirts/Transcripts/Tutorial%2025.files/image034.jpg" alt=""></strong></p><p><strong>I make a pattern of the gore which corresponds with the flare triangle with sides 9 and 10. </strong></p><p><strong><br><img class="img-responsive center-block" src="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/Dressmaker_Essential_Skirts/Transcripts/Tutorial%2025.files/image036.jpg" alt=""></strong></p><p><strong><br><img class="img-responsive center-block" src="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/Dressmaker_Essential_Skirts/Transcripts/Tutorial%2025.files/image038.jpg" alt=""></strong></p><p><strong><br><img class="img-responsive center-block" src="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/Dressmaker_Essential_Skirts/Transcripts/Tutorial%2025.files/image040.jpg" alt=""></strong></p><p><strong>And, finally, I make a pattern of the last gore which corresponds with the flare triangle in the middle of the back. </strong>This gore is made with a fold line because there will be the central back seam in the middle of it. I don’t need to add anything to it: only a seam allowance.</p><p><img class="img-responsive center-block" src="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/Dressmaker_Essential_Skirts/Transcripts/Tutorial%2025.files/image042.jpg" alt=""></p><p><strong>As the result, we have paper patterns of all parts of our half-scale mock-up skirt. </strong>I want to emphasize that the mock-up skirt was cut after a pattern which had been adjusted to match client’s measurements (in our case, measurements taken off the half-scale dress-form).</p><p><img class="img-responsive center-block" src="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/Dressmaker_Essential_Skirts/Transcripts/Tutorial%2025.files/image044.jpg" alt=""></p><p><strong>It is quite possible that your pattern might fit other close sizes depending on the type and style of the skirt you are making. </strong></p><p>My mock-up skirt, <strong>for example, </strong>features side seams. And this means I can let in or take out fabric to slightly adjust the size of the skirt up or down.</p><p><strong>It is also relatively easy to change the amount of flare. </strong>You can cut up the triangular insert patterns along the midline and increase or decrease the amount of flare by spreading the halves apart or overlapping them.</p><p><img class="img-responsive center-block" src="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/Dressmaker_Essential_Skirts/Transcripts/Tutorial%2025.files/image046.jpg" alt=""></p><p><strong>And if you want to add a train to the skirt, simply trim the corresponding gores down to the length of the skirt. </strong></p><p><strong><br><img class="img-responsive center-block" src="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/Dressmaker_Essential_Skirts/Transcripts/Tutorial%2025.files/image048.jpg" alt=""></strong></p><p><strong>And now let me tell you how to turn a half-scale pattern into a full-size pattern. </strong></p><p><strong>Of course, the easiest way to do it is to use Photoshop </strong>or any other image editing software where you can scale up a scanned image and then divide it in sheets of different sizes.</p><p><img class="img-responsive center-block" src="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/Dressmaker_Essential_Skirts/Transcripts/Tutorial%2025.files/image050.jpg" alt=""></p><p>The same task will take you a little longer <strong>if you don’t know how to use such software. </strong>You will have to cut out every separate part of the half-scale mock-up and re-draw it proportionally on graph paper doubling all widths and lengths manually.</p><p><strong>In conclusion, I would like to point out that working with a half-scale mock-up does speed up the process considerably and, more importantly, allows you to get a more precise pattern. </strong>There is a larger margin of error when you sew a full-size mock-up and transfer its parts on paper or fabric. The thing is that large pieces tend to stretch out and deform, and it is harder to work with them than with small pieces.</p><p><strong>I highly recommend you make your mock-ups in half scale. </strong></p><p><strong>Moreover, please note </strong>that I was aligning the lengthwise grain guidelines with the vertical gridlines very strictly when I was transferring the mock-up pieces on graph paper. It is compulsory to maintain the right direction of lengthwise grain when cutting fabric, too! This rule concerns all parts of the skirt regardless of their size. In the gores, the lengthwise grain will be about parallel to the vertical midline of the gore, which will make fabric stretch more evenly and help the gore hold its shape better. The gore with the fold line will have the lengthwise grain going right along the fold line.</p><p><strong>And now I will cut out all parts of the pattern, cut them from fabric, and sew a mock-up skirt to show you the results of our work. </strong></p></div> <!-- Itemprop END: articleBody --></div> <!-- Scope END: Article --><!-- END Schema.org microdata added by the Add-Meta-Tags WordPress plugin --> 					</div>															<div role="tabpanel" class="tab-pane" id="pattern">						<h3>Automatic&nbsp;Calculation Tables of All Parameters Required:</h3><p><strong><a href="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/Dressmaker_Essential_Skirts/Tables/sun/index.htm" target="_blank">Trapeze-Shaped Skirt</a></strong></p><p><strong><a href="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/Dressmaker_Essential_Skirts/Tables/halfSun/index.htm" target="_blank">Half-Circle Skirt</a></strong></p><p><strong><a href="ht